    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1894-12-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1894-12-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="361" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d361">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Gresham</persName> to
                                Baron <persName type="to">Fava</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1894-12-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 10,
                                    1894</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your note of the 27th ultimo, and to inform you in reply that
                            inasmuch as it appears from the statements therein contained that the
                            importation of salt into Sicily and Sardinia is not prohibited, and that
                            salt imported from the United States is admitted free of duty, the
                            collectors of customs at the principal ports of the United States were,
                            on the 7th instant, instructed to admit salt imported from those islands
                            to entry free of duty.</p>
                <p>Accept, Mr. Ambassador, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. Q. Gresham.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
